Q("Advertisement Serving","ad-serving","Advertising","Select eligible ads, pace budgets, and record billable events within a strict latency budget.","1M requests/s · p99 < 80 ms · billions of campaigns",["Publisher SDK","Ad Gateway","Eligibility Service","Budget / Pacing","Candidate Index","Auction Ranker"],["Precompute campaign eligibility into memory indexes; querying the campaign database on every impression cannot meet latency or QPS.","Reserve budget approximately on the hot path and reconcile exactly in the ledger; global serial counters would destroy availability.","Separate selection from billing evidence: clicks and impressions are signed, deduplicated events processed under fraud and attribution windows."],["How do you pace a daily budget?","How is an auction ranked?","How do you avoid overspend?","How is frequency capping stored?","How are fraudulent clicks handled?"]),
Q("Stock Exchange","stock-exchange","Transactions","Accept orders, match deterministically, publish market data, and preserve an auditable ledger.","5M orders/s · microsecond matching · strict price-time priority",["Trading Client","Order Gateway","Risk Check","Symbol Router","Matching Engine","Order Book"],["Route one symbol to one deterministic matching sequencer; parallel writers would require coordination on every price level and compromise price-time priority.","Persist an ordered command/event journal before external acknowledgment, then rebuild books by replay instead of synchronously updating many stores.","Market-data publication is derived and may lag matching; the execution ledger is authoritative and independently reconciled."],["How does price-time priority work?","How do you recover a matching engine?","How are market orders protected?","How is market data fanned out?","How do trading halts work?"]),
Q("Food Delivery Marketplace","food-delivery","Geo & Realtime","Coordinate menus, orders, restaurants, couriers, dispatch, and settlement in real time.","5M orders/day · courier updates every 5 s · dispatch < 3 s",["Customer App","Restaurant App","Courier App","Order API","Menu / Availability","Dispatch Engine"],["The order is a versioned state machine; restaurant acceptance, payment, preparation, pickup, and delivery are not one distributed transaction.","Live courier location belongs in an ephemeral geo index while order, assignment, and settlement remain durable.","Dispatch optimizes ETA and fairness with short offers/leases; forcing one courier choice synchronously makes stale GPS and disconnects catastrophic."],["How do restaurants update availability?","How do you avoid two couriers accepting?","How is ETA predicted?","How do cancellations compensate?","How are batched deliveries handled?"]),
Q("Hotel Reservation Platform","hotel-reservation","Transactions","Search inventory and reserve room-night capacity without overselling across channels.","10M searches/s · 100K hotels · zero unauthorized oversell",["Traveler Client","Search API","Hotel Catalog","Availability Index","Rate Service","Reservation API"],["Search uses eventually consistent materialized availability, but booking decrements authoritative room-night inventory with a conditional transaction.","Model inventory per room type and date; storing one aggregate hotel count makes multi-night atomic reservation and partial cancellation unsafe.","Use expiring quotes and idempotent booking commands because rates, taxes, and inventory can change between search and commit."],["How do multi-night bookings commit atomically?","How do cancellations restore inventory?","How do channel managers synchronize?","How do overbooking policies work?","How do you cache search results?"]),
Q("Digital Wallet","digital-wallet","Transactions","Hold balances, transfer value, enforce limits, and reconcile funding rails safely.","100K transfers/s · zero lost money · multi-currency",["Wallet Client","Wallet API","Identity / Limits","Transfer Orchestrator","Double-Entry Ledger","Balance Projection"],["The immutable double-entry ledger is truth; balances are projections with version checkpoints and can be rebuilt.","Transfer idempotency belongs at the command boundary, not the HTTP retry layer alone, because clients and workers can both repeat work.","External top-up and withdrawal rails are sagas with uncertain outcomes; reserve funds and reconcile provider references before final state."],["How do pending balances work?","How are transfers made idempotent?","How do chargebacks affect balances?","How do you support multiple currencies?","How do you reconcile a bank rail?"]),
Q("Expense Sharing","expense-sharing","Low-Level Design","Model groups, split strategies, debts, settlements, and simplified balances without losing history.","10M users · groups up to 1K · auditable revisions",["Mobile Client","Expense API","Group Aggregate","Split Strategy","Debt Graph","Settlement Service"],["Store immutable expenses and participant shares; current pairwise balances are derived so edits and deletions can reverse prior effects cleanly.","Strategy interfaces support equal, exact, percentage, and share splits while one validator enforces totals and currency precision.","Debt simplification is an optional projection: minimizing transfers changes who owes whom and must never replace the original obligations."],["How do percentage splits validate?","How are expenses edited?","How does debt simplification work?","How do currencies differ?","How do concurrent group edits resolve?"]),
Q("Online Auction","auction-platform","Transactions","Run timed auctions, enforce bid ordering, extend deadlines, and settle winners consistently.","1M concurrent bidders · p99 bid < 150 ms · hot celebrity lots",["Bidder Client","Auction Gateway","Auction Service","Bid Sequencer","Auction State","Bid Journal"],["Serialize bids per auction partition to enforce monotonic price and deterministic tie ordering; cross-auction work scales independently.","A bid journal is authoritative evidence, while current highest bid is a projection guarded by expected sequence.","Use server time and a versioned closing transition; anti-sniping extension must be part of the atomic bid decision, not a later timer."],["How do you handle simultaneous bids?","How does anti-sniping work?","How are payment failures handled?","How do proxy bids work?","How do you shard a hot auction?"]),
Q("Maps and Navigation","maps-navigation","Geo & Realtime","Serve maps, geocode places, compute routes, and update travel times from live traffic.","1B route requests/day · continental graph · p99 < 1 s",["Maps Client","Tile CDN","Geocoding API","Route API","Graph Partition Router","Road Graph Shards"],["Map tiles are immutable/versioned CDN objects; route computation uses a compact road graph and cannot scan raw geographic records per request.","Precompute contraction hierarchies or landmarks for fast routes, then overlay recent closures and traffic without rebuilding the base graph.","Partition geographically with boundary-node exchange; long routes use hierarchical planning to avoid fan-out across every shard."],["How do traffic updates affect routes?","How are map tiles generated?","How do you route across partitions?","How does offline navigation work?","How do you support multiple travel modes?"]),
Q("Service Discovery","service-discovery","Control Planes","Register instances, publish health-aware endpoints, and provide stable discovery through partitions.","10M instances · updates in seconds · lookup < 5 ms",["Service Instance","Registration Agent","Health Prober","Discovery API","Consensus Catalog","Change Log"],["The catalog requires a consistent membership generation, but clients should resolve from local caches to keep discovery off the request hot path.","Lease-based registration removes dead instances without trusting explicit deregistration; health status and ownership generation prevent stale resurrection.","Push watches reduce staleness but require resume cursors and snapshot fallback; pure polling is simpler at small fleets."],["How are stale instances removed?","Push or pull discovery?","How do clients survive catalog outage?","How is multi-region discovery handled?","How does DNS-based discovery compare?"]),
Q("Secrets Management","secrets-management","Security","Store, authorize, rotate, lease, and audit secrets without exposing plaintext broadly.","Millions secrets · 100K reads/s · HSM-backed root keys",["Workload Identity","Secrets API","Policy Engine","HSM / KMS","Encrypted Secret Store","Lease Issuer"],["Use envelope encryption so the database never holds plaintext or root keys; HSM calls protect key operations rather than every application byte.","Short-lived dynamic credentials reduce blast radius but introduce lease renewal and dependency availability costs.","Authorization is identity/resource/action-specific and every read is audited; caching plaintext broadly defeats the service boundary."],["How does envelope encryption work?","How are secrets rotated?","What if KMS is unavailable?","How do dynamic database credentials work?","How do applications bootstrap identity?"]),
Q("CI/CD Platform","ci-cd-platform","Developer Infrastructure","Trigger reproducible builds, schedule isolated runners, preserve artifacts, and deploy safely.","1M builds/day · untrusted code · petabytes of artifacts",["Git Provider","Webhook Ingest","Pipeline API","Workflow Compiler","Scheduler","Runner Pool"],["Compile declarative pipelines into immutable DAG executions; dynamic ad-hoc orchestration makes retries and audit impossible.","Run untrusted builds in ephemeral sandboxes with scoped credentials and network policy; sharing warm workers trades speed for isolation risk.","Artifacts and logs are immutable outputs, while deployment promotion is a separate, policy-gated state transition."],["How are runners isolated?","How does build caching work?","How do retries preserve semantics?","How are secrets injected?","How do progressive deployments work?"]),
Q("Package Registry","package-registry","Developer Infrastructure","Publish immutable packages, resolve versions, scan artifacts, and distribute them globally.","1B downloads/day · 100M versions · strong namespace integrity",["Package Client","Registry API","Namespace Auth","Metadata DB","Blob Store","Index / Resolver"],["Package blobs are content-addressed and immutable; mutable metadata points versions/tags to verified hashes.","Publish uses a staged upload and atomic metadata commit so resolvers never observe a version with missing bytes.","Dependency resolution is client or service policy, but every result pins exact versions/hashes to make builds reproducible."],["How do you prevent dependency confusion?","How are packages scanned?","Can a version be deleted?","How does CDN caching work?","How do private namespaces work?"]),
Q("Workflow Orchestrator","workflow-orchestrator","Infrastructure","Run durable multi-step workflows that survive retries, timers, worker crashes, and long waits.","100M active workflows · years-long history · deterministic replay",["Workflow Client","Workflow API","History Store","Workflow Task Queue","Deterministic Executor","Activity Queues"],["Persist workflow history, not in-memory stack state; deterministic replay reconstructs decisions after any worker failure.","Activities perform external side effects and must be idempotent; workflow code only schedules and records decisions.","Timers and signals are durable events, which costs history growth but avoids keeping processes or database locks alive for days."],["What makes workflow code deterministic?","How are activities retried?","How do you version workflow definitions?","How do timers scale?","How do child workflows work?"]),
Q("Distributed SQL Database","distributed-sql","Distributed Data","Provide SQL transactions over sharded, replicated data with online rebalancing.","PB-scale · millions TPS · serializable option",["SQL Client","SQL Gateway","Parser / Optimizer","Range Router","Transaction Coordinator","Timestamp Oracle"],["Range partitions preserve ordered scans while splitting hot ranges; hash sharding is simpler for point workloads but destroys locality.","Consensus replicates each range; distributed transactions coordinate only the ranges touched and pay latency proportional to geography.","MVCC enables consistent snapshots and online reads, but garbage collection must honor active transactions, backups, and change feeds."],["How does two-phase commit recover?","How are ranges split?","How is serializable isolation implemented?","What happens to long transactions?","How do schema changes run online?"]),
Q("Identity and Authentication","identity-auth","Security","Authenticate humans and services, issue sessions/tokens, enforce MFA, and revoke compromised access.","1B identities · global login · p99 < 300 ms",["User / Workload","Auth Gateway","Credential Verifier","MFA Service","Risk Engine","Session Issuer"],["Passwords or keys are verified in a narrow hardened boundary; application services consume short-lived signed assertions rather than credentials.","Short access tokens improve availability while refresh/session state enables revocation; fully stateless JWTs make immediate revocation expensive.","Risk and MFA are adaptive policy decisions with auditable versions, not hard-coded branches scattered across login clients."],["Session cookie or JWT?","How does token revocation work?","How are passwords stored?","How does account recovery work?","How do service identities differ?"]),
Q("Spreadsheet Engine","spreadsheet-engine","Low-Level Design","Model cells, formulas, dependencies, recalculation, cycles, and collaborative edits.","1M cells/sheet · incremental recalc · versioned edits",["Spreadsheet UI","Workbook Controller","Cell Store","Formula Parser","Dependency Graph","Cycle Detector"],["Store formulas separately from computed values; the dependency graph decides the minimal recalculation frontier after an edit.","Topological incremental evaluation avoids recomputing the workbook, while volatile functions require explicit invalidation policy.","Separate pure formula evaluation from I/O or user-defined functions so caching, determinism, and sandboxing remain defensible."],["How are cycles detected?","How does incremental recalculation work?","How are ranges represented?","How do concurrent edits merge?","How are volatile functions handled?"]),
